The International Court of Justice’s hearings on the boundary dispute between Kenya and Somalia continue without Nairobi’s participation, with Mogadishu set to exploit a legal provision to capitalise on the one-sided proceedings.  

According to the statute establishing the ICJ, failure by one party to appear does not prevent the proceedings from taking their course, rather, it opens a window for the participating party to press for a judgment in its favour in the absence of the defendant. 



